An oscilloscope is typically used to observe a signal voltage that varies with time. Oscilloscopes are powerful tools because they can be used to observe the exact wave shape of an electrical signal. The conventional oscilloscope works essentially like an older TV set: a cathode ray tube (CRT) generates an electron beam that strikes a fluorescent screen. The beam can be deflected in the _x_\-_y_ plane by a voltage applied to one of two sets of parallel plates. To measure the waveform of the signal, a _vertical amplifier_ applies a voltage to the _y_\-deflection plates that is proportional to the incoming signal. To measure the variance of the signal with time, a sawtooth voltage is applied to the _x_\-deflection plates, causing the beam to “sweep” continuously from right to left at a constant (adjustable) speed. The combination of the _x_ and _y_ motions causes the electron beam to trace out a plot of the input voltage as a function of time. In addition to the amplitude of the signal, an oscilloscope can show distortion, the time between two events (such as pulse width, period, or rise time) and relative timing of two related signals. We’ll take advantage of this latter property to measure the speed of light through a coaxial cable.

## Background

The basic oscilloscope, as shown in the figure above, is typically divided into four sections: the display, vertical controls, horizontal controls, and trigger controls. Even though you will be working and learning to use a particular oscilloscope, namely the Tektronix TBS-1072B, most of what you will learn today is generic and will apply to other oscilloscopes. The display is usually a CRT or LCD panel which is laid out with both horizontal and vertical reference lines referred to as the graticule. The graticule is laid out in an 8 by 10 division pattern. Each vertical and horizontal line constitutes a major division. The tick marks on the center horizontal and vertical graticule lines are called minor divisions. It is uncanny to observe that all oscilloscopes work essentially the same with the buttons at the same place. In fact, I have never seen an oscilloscope graticule that is not 8-by-10. Don’t ask me why, it is just the way it is. The labeling on the oscilloscope controls (such as volts/div and sec/div) always refers to major divisions.

In addition to the screen, most display sections are equipped with three basic controls.

- The **vertical section** controls the amplitude of the displayed signal. This section carries a Volts-per-Division (Volts/Div) selector knob, an AC/DC/Ground selector switch and the vertical (primary) input for the instrument. Additionally, this section is typically equipped with the vertical beam position knob.
- The **horizontal section** controls the time base or “sweep” of the instrument. The primary control is the Seconds-per-Division (Sec/Div) selector switch. Also included is a horizontal input for plotting dual _X_\-_Y_ axis signals. The horizontal beam position knob is generally located in this section.
- The **trigger** section controls the start event of the sweep. The trigger can be set to automatically restart after each sweep, or it can be configured to respond to an internal or external event. An external trigger input (EXT Input) and level adjustment is also included.

## Function Generator

A function generator is an electronic device or instrument that produces different types of electrical waveforms at various frequencies and amplitudes. It creates standard wave shapes like sine waves, square waves, triangle waves, and sawtooth waves, which are essential for testing, troubleshooting, and developing electronic circuits and systems.

The primary purpose of a function generator is to provide a reliable and controllable signal source. Engineers and technicians use it to test how electronic circuits respond to different input signals. For example, when developing an audio amplifier, they might use a function generator to input sine waves at various frequencies to test the amplifier's frequency response and distortion characteristics.

Function generators typically allow users to adjust several key parameters: the waveform type, frequency (how many cycles occur per second), amplitude (the signal's strength or voltage), and offset (the DC component of the signal). More advanced function generators might also offer features like frequency sweeping, where the frequency automatically changes over time, or burst mode, where the signal is output in controlled pulses.

In educational settings, function generators are valuable tools for teaching concepts in electronics and signal processing. Students can visualize how different waveforms behave and understand fundamental principles like frequency, period, and phase relationships. When connected to an oscilloscope, students can observe these waveforms in real time and measure their characteristics.

Common applications include testing audio equipment, calibrating measuring instruments, troubleshooting electronic devices, and developing new electronic products. In research laboratories, function generators are essential for experiments involving signal processing, communications systems, and electronic circuit design.

### Measuring the frequency of a signal

Let me explain how to measure the period of a sinusoidal signal using an oscilloscope.

First, connect the function generator's output to one of the oscilloscope's input channels using a BNC cable. Set the function generator to produce a sine wave at your desired frequency.

On the oscilloscope:

Start by adjusting the vertical scale (volts/division) until your signal takes up about 2/3 of the screen height. This gives you a clear view of the waveform without clipping.

Next, adjust the horizontal scale (time/division) until you can see 2-3 complete cycles of your sine wave. Having multiple cycles helps ensure accurate measurement and allows you to verify the signal is stable.

To measure the period, most modern digital oscilloscopes offer several methods:

Method 1 - Using cursors:

1. Enable the time cursors (usually through a "Cursor" button)
2. Place the first cursor at a specific point on the waveform (like a zero crossing)
3. Place the second cursor at the same point on the next cycle
4. Read the time difference (Δt) between cursors - this is your period

Method 2 - Using automatic measurements:

1. Press the "Measure" or "Quick Meas" button
2. Select "Period" from the measurement options
3. The oscilloscope will automatically display the period measurement

For the most accurate measurements, try to:

- Use the rising zero crossing points as reference points
- Ensure your trigger is stable (adjust trigger level if needed)
- Check that your signal isn't being distorted by improper amplitude settings
- Take multiple measurements and average them if high precision is needed

The frequency of your signal can be calculated from the period using f = 1/T, where T is the measured period. Most oscilloscopes will display both period and frequency

## Measuring the speed of light

This is a fascinating application of test equipment to measure a fundamental physical constant! Let me explain the process:

The basic principle relies on measuring the time delay between when a signal enters one end of a coaxial cable and when it arrives at the other end. Since we know the cable's length, we can calculate the speed of the signal (which travels at the speed of light in the cable's dielectric material).

Here's the step-by-step measurement process:

First, we set up the function generator to produce a sharp square wave signal at a relatively high frequency (say 10 MHz). The quick-rising edge of this square wave will be our timing reference.

We connect the function generator's output to:

1\. One channel of the oscilloscope (this is our timing reference)

2\. One end of the coaxial cable

The other end of the coaxial cable connects to the second channel of the oscilloscope.

When we look at the oscilloscope display, we'll see two square waves:

- - The original signal from the function generator (let's say on Channel 1)
    - The delayed signal that traveled through the cable (on Channel 2)

The oscilloscope will show a time difference (Δt) between these signals - this is the propagation delay through the cable. Using the oscilloscope's time measurement features, we can measure this delay very precisely, often in nanoseconds.

If we know the length of the cable (L), we can calculate the speed of the signal using:

v = L/Δt

The speed we calculate will be slower than the speed of light in vacuum (c) because the signal travels more slowly in the cable's dielectric material. The ratio of c to the measured speed gives us the cable's velocity factor (VF), which is typically around 0.66 for standard coaxial cable, meaning the signal travels at about 66% of the speed of light in vacuum.

For example, if we have:

- Cable length = 100 meters
- Measured delay = 500 nanoseconds

Then:

v = 100 meters / 500 nanoseconds = 2 × 10⁸ meters/second

This is roughly 2/3 of the speed of light in a vacuum (3 × 10⁸ m/s), which is exactly what we'd expect for a typical coax cable.

This measurement technique is not only educational but also practical - it's used in cable manufacturing to verify cable specifications and in network testing to determine cable lengths and locate breaks or faults in cables.
